"Blasi C., Michetti L., Del Moro M.A., Testa O., Teodonio L.","Climate change and desertification vulnerability in Southern Italy",2007,"Phytocoenologia","37","3-4",,"495","521",,,10.1127/0340-269X/2007/0037-0495,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-42549103212&partnerID=40&md5=1b3009355577d8eeb1020cec0cc1c041","Department of Plant Biology, University of Rome La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro 5, 00185 Rome, Italy","Blasi, C., Department of Plant Biology, University of Rome La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro 5, 00185 Rome, Italy; Michetti, L., Department of Plant Biology, University of Rome La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro 5, 00185 Rome, Italy; Del Moro, M.A., Department of Plant Biology, University of Rome La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro 5, 00185 Rome, Italy; Testa, O., Department of Plant Biology, University of Rome La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro 5, 00185 Rome, Italy; Teodonio, L., Department of Plant Biology, University of Rome La Sapienza, Piazzale Aldo Moro 5, 00185 Rome, Italy","The Rio de Janeiro Conference (1992) brought the state of health of the environment and global warming to the focus of attention. As a contribution to ongoing studies in this regard, this paper investigates whether, over protracted periods during the 20th century, climate change occurred in two regions of southern Italy - Puglia and Sicilia. A twofold approach was adopted: firstly, climate long time series describing the thermopluviometric regimes of the two regions were examined for trends, using as a basis data on monthly rainfall (mm) and minimum/maximum temperature (°C). For Puglia, both the rainfall and temperature data used were those recorded at 21 stations during the period 1921-2001, whereas for Sicilia data recorded at 18 stations was used, however the rainfall data was for the period 1956-2000, while temperature data was for the period 1924-2003. Secondly, a comparison was made between the RIVAS-MARTINEZ ombrothermic indices for the two periods 1955-1985 and 1986-2000. Both regression-analysis results and RIVASs-MARTINEZ indices indicate an increase in aridity and thus a growing vulnerability to desertification. However, any climate change under way can be greatly influenced by local orographic systems, meaning that different trends may be found even at stations located relatively close to each other. There is no uniform pattern to the trends in climate change emerging from the statistical analyses undertaken here. Therefore local government planning needs to take account of factors at a global scale (at the level of the Mediterranean basin as a whole), as well as factors at a regional and local scale, which are more closely linked to specific geomorphological characteristics. © 2007 Gebrüder Borntraeger.","Climatic parameters; Desertification; Ombrothermic indices; Regression analysis; Sicilia and Puglia","aridity; climate change; desertification; environmental conditions; global warming; regression analysis; time series analysis; vulnerability; Eurasia; Europe; Italy; Puglia; Sicily; Southern Europe",,,,,,"Alpert, P., Ben-Gai, T., Baharad, A., Benjamni, Y., Yekutieli, D., Colacino, M., Diodato, L., Manes, A., The paradoxical increase of Mediterranean extreme daily rainfall in spite of decrease in total values (2002) Geophys. Res. Letters, 11, p. 29; Arrigoni, P.V., Fitoclimatologia della Sardegna. (1968) Webbia, 23 (1), pp. 1-100; Biondi, E. & Baldoni, M. (1991): Bio-climatic characteristics of the italian peninsula. - In: Proceedings of the Conference Effetti degli inquinanti atmosferici sul clima e la vegetazione held in Taormina, 26-29 September 1991, pp. 225-250Biondi, E. & Baldoni, M. (1995): A possible method for geographic delimitation of phytoclimatic types with application to the phytoclimate of the Marche region of Italy. - Doc. Phytosoc. 15: 15-28Blasi, C. & MiChetti, L. (2005): Biodiversità e Clima. - In: Nature Protection Department of the Italian Ministry for the Environment (eds.): Stato della Biodiversita in 